      <title>At least 20 children injured after Delta aircraft dumps jet fuel over school</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANDelta Airlines Flight 89 was enroute to Shanghai from Los Angeles International Airport on Tuesday when the plane experienced an engine issue shortly after takeoff. The plane then proceeded to return to the airport and release jet fuel before conducting an emergency landing. The jet fuel was dumped over a Los Angeles schoolyard and school buildings, reports NBC News. According to the Los Angeles County Fire Department, at least 20 children and 11 adults are being treated for minor injuries for fuel exposure. Those affected were being treated by firefighters on the scene for skin irritation and breathing problems.The fire department said none of the injured needed to be hospitalized.The airline explained the release of fuel is required as part of standard procedure to reach a safe landing weight, Reuters reports, citing a statement from Delta Airlines.In a statement on Twitter, the Federal Aviation Administration explained that there are special fuel-dumping procedures which require airplanes to release jet fuel over designated unpopulated areas. The agency said that the fuel is typically released at higher altitudes so that it dissolves before reaching the ground.The FAA said in the same statement that it is "thoroughly investigating" the circumstances around the incident.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Delta Airlines Flight 89 taking off2. Jet fuel being dumped over a school3. Victims of the incident4. How fuel-dumping procedures typically workVOICEOVER (in English): "Delta Airlines Flight 89 was enroute to Shanghai from Los Angeles International Airport on Tuesday when the plane experienced an engine issue shortly after takeoff." "The plane then proceeded to return to the airport and release jet fuel before conducting an emergency landing.""NBC News reports the jet fuel was dumped over a Los Angeles schoolyard and school buildings.""According to the Los Angeles County Fire Department, at least 20 children and 11 adults are being treated for minor injuries for fuel exposure.""Those affected were being treated by firefighters on the scene for skin irritation and breathing problems.""The fire department said none of the injured needed to be hospitalized.""In a statement on Twitter, the Federal Aviation Administration explained that there are special fuel-dumping procedures which require airplanes to release jet fuel over designated unpopulated areas.""The agency said that the fuel is typically released at higher altitudes so that it dissolves before reaching the ground."SOURCES: NBC News, Los Angeles Times, L.A. County Fire Department Twitter, Federal Aviation Administration Twitter, Reutershttps://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/17-kids-injured-after-delta-jet-dumps-fuel-l-playground-n1115586https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-01-14/tracking-delta-flight-89s-path-before-it-dumped-fuel-on-an-elementary-schoolhttps://twitter.com/LACoFDPIO/status/1217224364824752128https://twitter.com/FAANews/status/1217213895066169345/photo/1https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-01-14/why-did-delta-jet-dump-fuelhttps://www.reuters.com/article/us-california-airplane-school/delta-flight-dumps-fuel-on-l-a-school-26-treated-for-minor-injuries-idUSKBN1ZD2OP***]]></description>
