ns to cancers.""Cardiff University says in a press statement that one type of T-cells was found to possess a unique receptor that allows them to detect almost all cancer cells.""The BBC reports that scientists may be able to take blood from a cancer patient and isolate their T-cells.""The T-cells could then be reprogrammed by a harmless virus to grow the special receptor and cultured before the immune cells are reintroduced to fight the patient's cancer cells.""T-cells with the special receptors are able to ignore healthy cells and attack the cancerous tissue, including tumors, which normal T-cells cannot."SOURCES: Nature Immunology, Cardiff University, BBC https://www.nature.com/articles/s41590-019-0578-8https://www.cardiff.ac.uk/news/view/1749599-discovery-of-new-t-cell-raises-prospect-of-universal-cancer-therapyhttps://www.bbc.com/news/health-51182451***]]></description>
